Thanks for sharing gcp.js. I see why you’re still getting old data—the file you committed is corrupted and won’t even load, so your fetcher keeps using the previous JSON snapshot.
What’s broken in your gcp.js
Here are a few examples I can see in the uploaded file:

|| has been mangled into blank lines, e.g.

const attrs = sku?.attributes \
\
{};

should be:

const attrs = sku?.attributes || {};

Several if conditions lost their logical ORs

if (usage === "h" \
\
usage === "hour" \
\
usage === "hours")


should be:


if (usage === "h" || usage === "hour" || usage === "hours")

Regex alternations were broken into new lines (no |), e.g. in inferMachineType and others.
Some validations have the operator order broken:


if (!raw \
\
/^custom-/i.test(raw)) return null;

should be:

if (!raw || /^custom-/i.test(raw)) return null;

A few regexes have been escaped and bracketed incorrectly:

if (!/^\[a-z0-9\]+-\[a-z\]+\[a-z0-9\]\*-\d+$/i.test(name)) ...

should be 

if (!/^[a-z0-9]+-[a-z]+[a-z0-9]*-\d+$/i.test(name)) ...

Because of these syntax errors, require('../lib/gcp') throws and your workflow either fails before regeneration or falls back to the last published docs/data/gcp/gcp.prices.json — hence “old data.”
